# Laravel Cursor Rules
# Stack: Laravel 11+, PHP 8.2+, MySQL/PostgreSQL, Laravel Sanctum

## Project Structure
Follow Laravel conventions with these additions:
```
app/
  Http/
    Controllers/Api/    # All API controllers go here
    Requests/           # Form Request validation classes
    Resources/          # API Resources (transformers)
    Middleware/
  Models/               # Eloquent models
  Services/             # Business logic (keep controllers thin)
  Repositories/         # DB query abstraction (optional but recommended)
  Actions/              # Single-purpose action classes
  Enums/                # PHP 8.1+ backed enums
  Exceptions/           # Custom exception classes
database/
  migrations/
  seeders/
  factories/
routes/
  api.php               # All API routes
  web.php               # Only if serving Blade views
```

## PHP Standards
- PHP 8.2+ features are encouraged: readonly classes, enums, fibers, typed properties.
- Always declare strict types: `<?php declare(strict_types=1);`
- Use named arguments for clarity on functions with many params.
- Return types must be declared on all methods.
- Use constructor property promotion wherever possible.

## Controllers
- Controllers are thin — they only: validate input, call a Service/Action, return a response.
- Use dedicated `app/Http/Controllers/Api/` namespace for all API controllers.
- One controller per resource. Use `--api` flag when generating (`php artisan make:controller`).
- Use `__invoke()` for single-action controllers.
- Never put business logic inside controllers.

Example:
```php
class PostController extends Controller
{
    public function __construct(private PostService $postService) {}

    public function index(): JsonResponse
    {
        return response()->json(
            PostResource::collection($this->postService->getPaginated())
        );
    }

    public function store(StorePostRequest $request): JsonResponse
    {
        $post = $this->postService->create($request->validated());
        return response()->json(new PostResource($post), 201);
    }
}
```

## Validation
- Always use Form Request classes (`php artisan make:request`). Never validate in controllers directly.
- Return validation errors as JSON automatically (Laravel does this for API routes).
- Define `authorize()` properly — never just `return true` in production without thought.

## API Resources
- Transform all model data through `JsonResource` or `ResourceCollection`. Never return raw Eloquent models.
- Use `whenLoaded()` for relationships to avoid N+1 in responses.
- Keep resources in `app/Http/Resources/`.

## Models
- Always define `$fillable` (never use `$guarded = []` in production).
- Define relationships explicitly with return types.
- Use Eloquent scopes for reusable query logic.
- Cast attributes using the `$casts` property (or `casts()` method in Laravel 11).
- Never write raw SQL — use Eloquent or the Query Builder.

```php
class Post extends Model
{
    protected $fillable = ['title', 'body', 'user_id', 'status'];

    protected $casts = [
        'status' => PostStatus::class, // Enum cast
        'published_at' => 'datetime',
    ];

    public function user(): BelongsTo
    {
        return $this->belongsTo(User::class);
    }

    public function scopePublished(Builder $query): void
    {
        $query->where('status', PostStatus::Published);
    }
}
```

## Services
- Business logic lives in `app/Services/`. One service class per domain entity.
- Services are injected via constructor DI.
- Keep service methods focused and single-purpose.

## Routes (api.php)
- Prefix all routes with `api/` and version them: `/api/v1/`.
- Use `Route::apiResource()` for CRUD.
- Group routes by auth middleware: `auth:sanctum`.
- Name all routes explicitly.

```php
Route::prefix('v1')->group(function () {
    Route::post('/login', [AuthController::class, 'login']);

    Route::middleware('auth:sanctum')->group(function () {
        Route::apiResource('posts', PostController::class);
    });
});
```

## Authentication (Sanctum)
- Use Laravel Sanctum for API authentication.
- For SPA (Next.js on same domain/subdomain): use cookie-based Sanctum sessions.
- For mobile or cross-domain: use API tokens.
- Always run `CSRF` protection for cookie-based auth. Expose `/sanctum/csrf-cookie`.
- Set `SESSION_DOMAIN`, `SANCTUM_STATEFUL_DOMAINS`, and `CORS` settings correctly in `.env`.

## CORS
- Configure `config/cors.php` to allow your Next.js origin.
- Always set `supports_credentials: true` when using cookie auth.
- Never use `'*'` as `allowed_origins` in production.

## Error Handling
- Register custom error handling in `bootstrap/app.php` (Laravel 11) or `app/Exceptions/Handler.php`.
- Return consistent JSON error responses for API routes:
  ```json
  { "message": "...", "errors": { "field": ["..."] } }
  ```
- Use custom Exception classes for domain-specific errors.
- Map exceptions to proper HTTP status codes (400, 401, 403, 404, 422, 500).

## Database & Migrations
- Every schema change must have a migration.
- Never edit existing migrations after deployment — create new ones.
- Always add indexes on foreign keys and columns used in `WHERE` clauses.
- Use `unsignedBigInteger` for foreign keys; prefer `foreignId()->constrained()`.
- Soft deletes (`SoftDeletes`) for any user-generated content.

## Performance
- Eager load relationships to prevent N+1: `Post::with('user', 'tags')->get()`.
- Use pagination for all list endpoints (`->paginate()`).
- Cache expensive queries with `Cache::remember()`.
- Queue long-running tasks (emails, exports) with Laravel Queues.
- Use `php artisan optimize` in production.

## Security
- Never trust client input — always validate and sanitize.
- Use `policy` classes for authorization logic (`php artisan make:policy`).
- Check policies in controllers via `$this->authorize()`.
- Hash passwords with `bcrypt` or `Hash::make()`. Never store plain text.
- Rate limit sensitive endpoints with `ThrottleRequests` middleware.
- Keep `.env` out of version control. Use `.env.example` for documentation.

## Testing
- Write feature tests for all API endpoints (`tests/Feature/Api/`).
- Use `RefreshDatabase` trait to reset DB between tests.
- Use model factories for test data.
- Test happy path AND validation/auth failure cases.

```php
public function test_authenticated_user_can_create_post(): void
{
    $user = User::factory()->create();

    $response = $this->actingAs($user)->postJson('/api/v1/posts', [
        'title' => 'Test Post',
        'body' => 'Content here',
    ]);

    $response->assertCreated()->assertJsonStructure(['data' => ['id', 'title']]);
}
```

## Naming Conventions
- Controllers: `PascalCase`, singular (e.g., `PostController`)
- Models: `PascalCase`, singular (e.g., `Post`)
- Migrations: `snake_case` with verb (e.g., `create_posts_table`)
- Routes: `kebab-case` (e.g., `/api/v1/blog-posts`)
- Methods: `camelCase`
- Variables: `camelCase`
- Config/env keys: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`

## Don'ts
- Don't put logic in routes files.
- Don't use `dd()` or `dump()` in production code.
- Don't use `->get()` without pagination on large datasets.
- Don't skip Form Requests for validation.
- Don't return raw model data — always use API Resources.
- Don't hardcode credentials — use `.env`.
